{{About|the American actor and stand-up comedian|the mayor of New York 1926–1932|Jimmy Walker|other persons named Jimmy Walker|Jimmy Walker (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox person |image = Jimmie Walker 2015 (cropped).jpg |caption = (2015) |nationality = [[United States|American]] |known_for = James Evans Jr. ("J.J.") on the ''[[Good Times]]'' TV series |birth_name = James Carter Walker Jr. |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1947|6|25}} |birth_place = [[The Bronx, New York City]] |death_date = |death_place = |death_cause = |education = [[Theodore Roosevelt High School (New York City)|Theodore Roosevelt High School]] |occupation = Actor, comedian |years_active = 1969–present | website = {{url|http://jimmiejjwalkerdynomite.com/}} }} [[File:Good Times the Evans family 1974.JPG|thumb|275px|On ''[[Good Times]]'' (1974), L–R: [[Ralph Carter]], [[BernNadette Stanis]], Jimmie Walker, [[Esther Rolle]], and [[John Amos]]]]
'''James Carter Walker Jr.''' (born June 25, 1947) is an [[United States|American]] [[actor]] and [[stand-up comedian|comedian]]. Walker is best known for portraying James Evans Jr. ("J.J."), the oldest son of Florida and James Evans Sr. on the [[CBS]] [[television series]] ''[[Good Times]]'', which ran from [[1974 in television|1974]] to [[1979 in television|1979]]. Walker was nominated for [[Golden Globe]] awards ''Best Supporting Actor In A Television Series'' in 1975 and 1976 for his role. While on the show, Walker's character was known for the [[catchphrase]] ''"Dy-no-mite!"'' which he also used in his mid–1970s TV commercial for a [[Panasonic]] line of [[Compact Cassette|cassette]] and [[8-track tape]] players. He also starred in ''[[Let's Do It Again (1975 film)|Let's Do It Again]]'' with John Amos, and ''The Greatest Thing That Almost Happened'' with [[James Earl Jones]]. Walker continues to tour the country with his stand-up comedy routine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dynomitejj.com/gigs.asp |title=Jimmie JJ Walker's Gigs |accessdate=2008-08-18 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817141127/http://www.dynomitejj.com/gigs.asp |archivedate=2008-08-17 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=30 years after 'J.J.,' Walker still draws laughs.|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-17733368_ITM|date=2006-07-24|work=The Columbus Dispatch|accessdate=2008-08-18 | first=Michael | last=Grossberg}} (requires login)</ref>
==Early life== Walker was born in [[The Bronx, New York]]. Walker attended [[Theodore Roosevelt High School (New York City)|Theodore Roosevelt High School]] in [[New York City]]. Through a federal program known as ''SEEK,'' or "Search for Education, Evaluation, and Knowledge," he continued his studies and entered into the field of radio engineering with WRVR. As a young man, Walker was a vendor at [[Yankee Stadium]], starting with the [[1964 World Series]]. He was given a [[United States dollar coin|silver dollar]] by [[Mickey Mantle]], which he still has.
==Career== In 1967, Walker began working full-time with [[WLTW|WRVR]], the radio station of the [[Riverside Church]]. In 1969, Walker began performing as a [[stand-up comedian]] and was eventually discovered by the casting director for ''[[Good Times]]'', after making appearances on ''[[Rowan & Martin's Laugh In]]'' and on the ''[[Jack Paar|Jack Paar Show]]''. He eventually released one stand-up comedy album during the height of his ''Good Times'' popularity: ''Dyn-o-mite'' on Buddah Records (5635). During ''Good Times''<nowiki>'</nowiki> [[1974–75 United States network television schedule|1974–75 season]], Walker was 26 years old, though his character was much younger. [[John Amos]], the actor who portrayed Walker's father on ''Good Times,'' was actually just eight years older than Walker. Walker credits producer/director [[John Rich (director)|John Rich]] for inventing "Dy-no-mite!" which Rich insisted Walker say on every episode. Both Walker and executive producer [[Norman Lear]] were skeptical of the idea, but the phrase and Walker's character caught on with the audience.<ref name=CNN /> Also, off- and on-camera, Walker did not get along with series' lead, [[Esther Rolle]], who played [[Florida Evans]], in the series, because she and Amos disapproved of Walker's increasingly buffoonish character and his popularity, and Walker felt hurt by their disdain. Dissatisfaction led Amos (before Rolle), to leave the show, making Walker the star of the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sitcomsonline.com/boards/archive/index.php/t-53025.html|title=Was Jimmie Walker getting along with Esther Rolle and John Amos on the set? [Archive] - Sitcoms Online Message Boards - Forums|website=www.sitcomsonline.com|accessdate=30 July 2018}}</ref> Walker was the only ''Good Times'' star to not attend Rolle's funeral.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.6minutez.com/something-i-bet-you-didnt-know-esther-rolle-wanted-j-j-off-good-times/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-09-18 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008135050/http://www.6minutez.com/something-i-bet-you-didnt-know-esther-rolle-wanted-j-j-off-good-times/ |archivedate=2014-10-08 |df= }}</ref>
==Later career== During 1975 Walker was also a weekend personality on contemporary R&B music station KAGB 103.9 FM licensed to Inglewood in the Los Angeles market. Walker appeared on ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' and ''[[Match Game]]'' during the 1970s and early 1980s. He also appeared on the 1990 revival of ''[[Match Game]]'' and various game shows during that era. Walker has made guest appearances on ''[[Badge 373]]'', ''[[The Love Boat]]'', ''[[Fantasy Island]]'', ''[[The Larry Sanders Show]]'', ''[[Son of the Beach]]'', ''[[The Drew Carey Show]]'', ''[[The John Larroquette Show]]'', ''[[In the House (TV series)|In the House]]'', ''[[Cagney & Lacey]]'', ''[[The Fall Guy]]'', ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]'', ''[[Star Dates]]'', ''[[Everybody Hates Chris]]'', ''[[George Lopez (TV series)|George Lopez]]'', ''[[Chelsea Lately]]'' and ''[[Lincoln Heights (TV series)|Lincoln Heights]]''. He also appeared in films such as ''[[Rabbit Test (film)|Rabbit Test]]'' (1978), ''[[The Concorde ... Airport '79]]'' (1979), ''[[Airplane!]]'' (1980), ''[[Water (1985 film)|Water]]'' (1985), ''[[Doin' Time (film)|Doin' Time]]'' (1985), ''[[The Guyver]]'' (1991), ''[[Monster Mash (1995 film)|Monster Mash]]'' (1995) and ''[[Plump Fiction]]'' (1997). Aside from guest appearances, he starred in the short-lived television series ''[[At Ease (TV series)|At Ease]]'' in 1983 and ''[[Bustin' Loose (TV series)|Bustin' Loose]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yK8DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA58&dq=jimmie+walker&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjtnrLfyZ7OAhUGtxQKHf_6APEQ6AEIKzAD#v=onepage&q=jimmie+walker&f=false|title=Jet|first=Johnson Publishing|last=Company|date=2 November 1987|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company|accessdate=30 July 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref> in 1987. In the 1990s, Walker returned to his radio roots hosting shows on [[WHIO (AM)|WHIO]], [[WOAI (AM)|WOAI]], [[WLS (AM)|WLS]], and [[KOIL|KKAR]]. In 1996, he appeared on split release with [[Powerviolence]] band [[Spazz (band)|Spazz]] distributed by Spazz owned label Slap-a-ham records. In 2010, Walker made a cameo appearance in the movie ''[[Big Money Rustlas]]''. In 2011, Walker appeared in a [[Syfy]] channel movie ''Super Shark''. In 2012, Jimmie Walker's autobiography ''Dyn-o-mite! Good Times, Bad Times, Our Times – A Memoir'', was published. In 2012, Walker announced the release of his official app developed by Monty Goulet for [[iOS]].
==Personal life and political views== According to an appearance on ''[[The Wendy Williams Show]]'' on June 27, 2012, Walker stated he has never been married nor fathered children, but has had many girlfriends. Walker appeared on ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]'' on July 11, 2012. He stated that he did not vote for [[Barack Obama]] and that he would not vote for him in the 2012 election either.<ref name=OReilly>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/on-air/oreilly/2012/07/12/jimmie-jj-walker-enters-no-spin-zone|title=Jimmie 'J.J.' Walker enters No Spin Zone|publisher=Fox News|date=July 11, 2012|accessdate=February 12, 2013|quote=O'REILLY: Did you vote for him first time around? / WALKER: I never voted for him.|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120906060552/http://www.foxnews.com/on-air/oreilly/2012/07/12/jimmie-jj-walker-enters-no-spin-zone|archivedate=September 6, 2012|df=}}</ref> In an interview with [[CNN]], Walker described himself politically as a "realist independent" and stated that he opposed [[affirmative action in the United States|affirmative action]], saying that it had outlived its usefulness. He also said that he was against [[gay marriage]] on moral grounds, but believed its legalization should be passed, stating it was not worth fighting against.<ref name=CNN>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/07/16/showbiz/celebrity-news-gossip/jimmie-jj-walker-book|title=Jimmie 'J.J.' Walker lights 'Dy-no-mite' on gay marriage, Leno and dating|publisher=CNN|date=July 16, 2012|accessdate=February 12, 2012}}</ref>
Walker described his political beliefs at length in his autobiography, ''Dyn-O-Mite: Good Times, Bad Times, Our Times: A Memoir.'' In it, he called himself a "logicist," who believes in "logic and common sense", holding conservative positions on many issues.<ref>{{cite book | last=Walker | first=Jimmie | date=June 26, 2012 | title=Dyn-O-Mite: Good Times, Bad Times, Our Times: A Memoir | pages=194-203 | location=Boston | publisher=Da Capo Press | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q3EP1S7DiU4C | isbn=0-306-82083-8 }}</ref>
Despite rumors that Walker was dating conservative pundit and author [[Ann Coulter]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/ann-coulter-dates-jimmie-walker-norman-lear-article-1.3019509 |title=Ann Coulter ‘dates’ ‘Good Times’ star Jimmie Walker, says Norman Lear |last=Feldman |first=Kate |date=April 4, 2017 |website=www.nydailynews.com |publisher=NY Daily News |access-date=August 3, 2017 |quote="I’ll tell you something about him that’ll astound you: He dates Ann Coulter"}}</ref> they are just close friends.<ref>https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/celebrity/ann-coulter-denies-jimmie-walker-romance/ar-BBzssc2</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://decider.com/2017/04/05/ann-coulter-breaks-her-silence-on-jimmie-walker-romance-rumors/|title=Ann Coulter Breaks Her Silence On Jimmie Walker Romance Rumors|date=5 April 2017|publisher=|accessdate=30 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/tv/2017/04/03/norman-lear-jimmie-walker-dates-ann-coulter/|title=Norman Lear Says Jimmie Walker Dates Ann Coulter|publisher=|accessdate=30 July 2018}}</ref> On August 3, 2017, Walker publicly announced his support for President [[Donald Trump]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2017/08/03/good-times-star-jimmie-walker-supports-trump-slams-pc-culture.html |title='Good Times' star Jimmie Walker supports Trump, slams PC culture |last=Glines |first=Caroline |date=August 3, 2017 |website=www.foxnews.com |publisher=Fox News |access-date=August 3, 2017 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/good-times-star-jimmie-walker-supports-trump-defends-bill-maher-1026417 |title='Good Times' Star Jimmie Walker Supports Trump, Defends Bill Maher |last=Parker |first=Ryan |date=August 3, 2017 |website=www.hollywoodreporter.com |publisher=Hollywood Reporter |access-date=August 3, 2017 |quote=}}</ref> saying that he was "for probably 90 percent of the things he does."
